<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38158a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38158a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38158a"> 158(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Kitab-al-/Mayyitun</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">the French Egyptologists described it as a copy of the &ldquo;Rituel Fune&eacute;raire&rdquo; of the ancient Egyptians. Among these was Champollion le Jeune, but later, on his return from Egypt, he and others called it &ldquo;Le Livre des Morts,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Book of the Dead,&rdquo; &ldquo;Das Todtenbuch,&rdquo; etc. These titles are merely translations of the name given by the Egyptian tomb-robbers to every roll of inscribed papyrus which they found with mummies, namely, &ldquo;Kita&acirc;b-al-Mayyit,&rdquo; &ldquo;Book of the dead man,&rdquo; or &ldquo;<mark>Kita&acirc;b al-Mayyitun</mark>,&rdquo; &ldquo;Book of the dead&rdquo; (<i>plur</i>.). <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD2"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a> (1920) 2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
